Read Some Papers

Reading Post Slack Channel Link
Bowes, S. M., Costello, T. H., Ma, W., & Lilienfeld, S. O. (2021). Looking under the tinfoil hat: Clarifying the personological and psychopathological correlates of conspiracy beliefs. Journal of Personality, 89(3), 422-436. This week is a bit of an exploration. First choose an existing conspiracy or if you wish, make one up. Then develop a 7-15 item instrument in a Word document or PDF with the purpose of determining the level of belief that a person may exhibit in that conspiracy. Finally please post the following: (1) A brief description of your conspiracy, (2) your instrument, and (3) a few paragraphs describing how you would go about assessing the validity and reliability of your instrument. #conspiracy
Brotherton, R., French, C. C., & Pickering, A. D. (2013). Measuring belief in conspiracy theories: the generic conspiracist beliefs scale. Frontiers in psychology, 4, 279. ditto ditto ditto
Enders, A. M., & Smallpage, S. M. (2018). On the measurement of conspiracy beliefs. Research & Politics. ditto ditto ditto
